    },
    "detailed_description": "HttpUtils is a static utility class that encapsulates HTTP communication functionality using Apache HttpClient library. The class provides a comprehensive set of methods for making HTTP requests across all major HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE).\n\n**Core Functionality:**\n1. **HTTP GET Requests**: The `doGet` method allows sending GET requests with custom headers and query parameters.\n\n2. **HTTP POST Requests**: Three overloaded `doPost` methods support different body types:\n   - Form-encoded data (Map<String, String>)\n   - Raw string body (JSON/XML)\n   - Binary data (byte array)\n\n3. **HTTP PUT Requests**: Two overloaded `doPut` methods support:\n   - String body content\n   - Binary byte array content\n\n4. **HTTP DELETE Requests**: The `doDelete` method handles DELETE operations with headers and query parameters.\n\n5. **URL Building**: The private `buildUrl` method constructs properly encoded URLs by combining host, path, and query parameters with URL encoding.\n\n6. **SSL/HTTPS Support**: The `wrapClient` and `sslClient` methods configure the HttpClient for HTTPS connections using a trust-all certificate strategy (which is insecure for production use).\n\n**Implementation Characteristics:**\n- All public methods are static, making this a stateless utility class\n- Uses deprecated Apache HttpClient classes (DefaultHttpClient, ClientConnectionManager)\n- Implements an insecure SSL trust manager that accepts all certificates\n- All methods throw generic Exception rather than specific exception types\n- The 'method' parameter in all public methods is unused but passed as an argument",
    "responsibilities": [
      "Provide HTTP GET, POST, PUT, DELETE request capabilities with custom headers and query parameters",
      "Build properly URL-encoded request URLs from host, path, and query parameter components",
      "Handle SSL/HTTPS connections by configuring trust managers for secure protocol communication",
      "Support multiple request body formats including form-encoded data, string content, and binary byte arrays",
      "Wrap and configure Apache HttpClient instances for both HTTP and HTTPS protocols"
    ],
